      "message": "blocks: add `-reobfuscate-blocks` to xor existing blk/rev on startup\n\n### Context\n\nRecent discussions highlighted that many nodes which synced before Bitcoin Core v28.0 have their blk*.dat/rev*.dat stored effectively in the clear (zero XOR key). This patch adds a simple, resumable maintenance tool to obfuscate previously raw block files (pre-v28.0 datadirs), rotate an existing key to a fresh random one, or de-obfuscate (set key to zero) if consciously chosen, all without requiring resync. The operation can be cancelled and restarted safely.\n\n### Implementation\n\nThe new startup option `-reobfuscate-blocks[=VALUE]` accepts either 16 hex characters as an exact 8-byte XOR key (little-endian in-memory layout) or a boolean to generate a random 64-bit key. e.g. `-reobfuscate-blocks=0000000000000000` sets the key to zero, effectively removing obfuscation.\n\nAt startup, we iterate over all blk*.dat/rev*.dat files, read them with the old XOR key and write them back with the new key (<name>.reobfuscated). After successful write, we delete the old file. Once all files are staged, we rename them back and atomically swap `xor.dat.reobfuscated` → `xor.dat`.\n\nThe operation is:\n* Resumable if interrupted, re-obfuscation resumes automatically (detected via `xor.dat.reobfuscated`) even without the flag. In worst-case crash we only redo work.\n* Single-threaded, processing one file at a time to keep code simple and avoid complexity of interleaving renames and key swaps across threads.\n* Fast in practice with sequential read/modify/write per blockfile. After recent obfuscation vectorization, this path is very quick.\n\nWe log the old and new keys and print progress roughly per-percent as files complete (i.e. max 100 progress logs).\n\nSimilar attempts: #32451 and andrewtoth/blocks-xor\n\nCo-authored-by: Andrew Toth <andrewstoth@gmail.com>\nCo-authored-by: Murch <murch@murch.one>",
